#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:72
msgid "## Reverse Instructional Design (and Preparation!)"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:74
msgid ""
"When sitting down to plan a course or workshop, it might be tempting to dive into reviewing the content, questioning your\n"
"understanding, and anticipating questions that learners might have for you. While it is good to prepare your content, this\n"
"approach can take you down extended rabbit-holes in which you anticipate and research questions that only an expert\n"
"would think to ask, and never get around to thinking about how to get your learners from one point to the next, and how to\n"
"know when they've gotten there.  "
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:80
msgid ""
"This is a problem with curriculum design as well as preparation. When writing curriculum, it is easy to allow *content*\n"
"objectives to distract from *learning* objectives. One way to prevent this is to take a \"reverse\" approach to instruction, as\n"
"advanced in Wiggins and McTighe's *[Understanding by Design](http://www.worldcat.org/title/understanding-by-\n"
"design/oclc/56491025)*, that keeps the focus firmly on learning outcomes. The order of preparation in this case becomes"
msgstr ""

# ordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:85
msgid "1.  Determine your learning objectives"
msgstr ""

# ordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:86
msgid ""
"2.  Decide what constitutes evidence that objectives have been met, and "
"design assessments to target that evidence"
msgstr ""

# ordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:87
msgid ""
"3.  Design instruction: Sort assessments in order of increasing complexity, "
"and write content that connects everything together"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/15-lesson-study.md:89
msgid ""
"In the context of preparing for a Carpentries-style workshop, the lesson design has already occurred, and many lessons include\n"
"pre-written exercises to use for assessment. In this context, *reverse instructional design*  principles might be applied as\n"
"follows: 1) review the lesson's learning objectives carefully, thinking about how they will work for your audience, 2) scan\n"
"the lesson to identify promising points to check in with your learners, using formative assessment to verify that objectives have been met, and then 3) review the connecting content in detail to be sure everything works and you have anticipated likely problems and questions."
msgstr ""

